<!--********************************************************************-->

<section xml:id="common-matrix-commands">
	<title>Common Matrix Functions</title> 

	<objectives>
		<introduction>
			<p>
				By the end of this section, you will be able to ...
			</p>
		</introduction>
		<ol>
			<li>Apply various scientific functions to the values of a matrix,</li>
			<li>Compute the maximum or minimum of the values in a matrix, and</li>
			<li>Compute the sum or product of the values in a matrix.</li>
		</ol>
	</objectives>

	<introduction>
		<p>
			In this section, we will list some common built-in functions that apply to either each value of a matrix (element-wise) or on the rows or columns of the matrix (row/column-wise).
		</p>

	</introduction>

	<paragraphs xml:id="common-scientific-functions">
	<title><insert>Common Scientific Functions</insert></title><p/>

		<p>
			MATLAB also contains a large library of functions you might find on a scienfic/graphing calculator. Most of the common functions (e.g. <m>\sin, \cos, \log,</m> etc.) require a single number input. However, MATLAB, has designed these common functions to take a matrix as an input. In particular, MATLAB applies these functions element-wise, as shown below for the <m>\sin</m> function.
			<sidebyside>
			<p>
			<m>\sin</m> 
			<m>\left( \left[
				\begin{matrix} 
					A_{11} \amp A_{12} \amp \dots \amp A_{1n} \\
					A_{21} \amp A_{22} \amp \dots \amp A_{2n} \\
					\vdots \amp \vdots \amp \ddots \amp \vdots \\
					A_{m1} \amp A_{m2} \amp \dots \amp A_{mn} \\
				\end{matrix}
				\right]\right) = 
				\left[
				\begin{matrix} 
					\sin(A_{11}) 	\amp	\sin(A_{12})	\amp	\dots	\amp	\sin(A_{1n}) \\
					\sin(A_{21}) 	\amp	\sin(A_{22})	\amp	\dots	\amp	\sin(A_{2n}) \\
					\vdots 				\amp	\vdots 			\amp	\ddots	\amp	\vdots \\
					\sin(A_{m1}) 	\amp	\sin(A_{m2})	\amp	\dots	\amp	\sin(A_{mn}) \\
				\end{matrix}
				\right]
			</m>
			</p>
			</sidebyside>
		</p>

		<lemma xml:id="trig-radians-syntax">
		<title><em>Trigonometric Functions</em></title><p/>
			<statement>
				<sidebyside widths="100% 0%">
					<tabular>
						<col width="20%"/>
						<col width="80%"/>
						<row bottom="minor">
							<cell colspan="2"><p>Let <c>A</c> be an <m>m \times n</m> matrix variable containing values in radians.</p></cell>
						</row>
						<row>
							<cell><p>Command</p></cell>
							<cell><c>result = sin(A)</c>, <c>result = cos(A)</c>, <c>result = tan(A)</c></cell>
						</row>
						<row><cell/><cell><c>result = csc(A)</c>, <c>result = sec(A)</c>, <c>result = cot(A)</c></cell></row>
						<row valign="top">
							<cell><p>Output</p></cell>
							<cell>
								<p>
									<c>result</c> (<m>m \times n</m>) matrix containing the chosen trig function applied to each value in <c>A</c>.
								</p>
							</cell>
						</row>
						<row>
							<cell>Notes</cell>
							<cell>
								<p>
									If <c>A</c> contains degree values instead of radians, use the functions:
								</p>
							</cell>
						</row>
						<row><cell/><cell><c>result = sind(A)</c>, <c>result = cosd(A)</c>, <c>result = tand(A)</c></cell></row>
						<row><cell/><cell><c>result = cscd(A)</c>, <c>result = secd(A)</c>, <c>result = cotd(A)</c></cell></row>
					</tabular>
					<p/>
				</sidebyside>
			</statement>
		</lemma>

		<example xml:id="example-matrix-computations">
		<!--<title><em><term>Computations in a Matrix</term></em></title>-->
			<p/>
			<p>
				Let <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> be given by
				<me>
					A = \left[
					\begin{matrix}
						\pi 	\amp	0			\amp 2 \\
						2\pi 	\amp	\pi/2	\amp 4 \\
					\end{matrix}\right], \qquad
					B = \left[
					\begin{matrix}
						0	\amp	30	\amp	60	\amp	90 \\
					\end{matrix}\right]
				</me>
			</p>

			<p>
				where <m>A</m> contains radian values and <m>B</m> contains degree values.
			</p>

			<p>
				Give the MATLAB command that 
				<ol marker="a">
					<li>defines, <c>sin_A</c>, as the matrix containing the <m>\sin</m> of all the values in <c>A</c>.</li>
					<li>defines, <c>cos_B</c>, as the matrix containing the <m>\cos</m> of all the values in <c>B</c>.</li>
				</ol>
				Recall, the MATLAB constant for <m>\pi</m> is <c>pi</c>.
			</p>

			<p/>

			<solution>
				<p>
					Since the values in <c>A</c> are in radians and the values in <c>B</c> are in degrees, we use the commands
					<sidebyside width="100%">
						<program language="matlab">
							<code>
								A = [pi 0 2;2*pi pi/2 4];
								sin_A = sin(A)
								B = [0 30 60 90];
								cos_B = cosd(A)
							</code>
						</program>
					</sidebyside>
				</p>

				<p>
					Running these commands, gives the output
					<sidebyside width="100%">
						<program language="matlab">
							<code>
								sin_A =

									 0.0000         0    0.9093
									-0.0000    1.0000   -0.7568

								cos_B =

									0.9985    1.0000    0.9994
									0.9940    0.9996    0.9976
							</code>
						</program>
					</sidebyside>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</example>

		<lemma xml:id="exp-log-sqrt-syntax">
		<title><em><c>exp</c>,<c>log</c>, and <c>sqrt</c> functions</em></title><p/>
			<statement>
				<sidebyside widths="100% 0%">
					<tabular>
						<col width="20%"/>
						<col width="80%"/>
						<row bottom="minor">
							<cell colspan="2"><p>Let <c>A</c> be an <m>m \times n</m> matrix variable.</p></cell>
						</row>
						<row>
							<cell><p>Command</p></cell>
							<cell><c>result = exp(A)</c> (exponential function, <m>e^x</m>), </cell>
						</row>
						<row valign="top" bottom="minor">
							<cell><p>Output</p></cell>
							<cell><p><c>result</c> (<m>m \times n</m>) matrix containing the exponent of each value in <c>A</c>.</p></cell>
						</row>
						<row>
							<cell><p>Command</p></cell>
							<cell><p><c>result = log(A)</c> (natural logarithm function, <m>\ln x</m>),</p></cell>
						</row>
						<row valign="top" bottom="minor">
							<cell><p>Output</p></cell>
							<cell><p><c>result</c> (<m>m \times n</m>) matrix containing the natural log of each value in <c>A</c>.</p></cell>
						</row>
						<row>
							<cell><p>Command</p></cell>
							<cell><c>result = sqrt(A)</c> (square root function, <m>\sqrt{x}</m>), </cell>
						</row>
						<row valign="top" bottom="minor">
							<cell><p>Output</p></cell>
							<cell><p><c>result</c> (<m>m \times n</m>) matrix containing the square root of each value in <c>A</c>.</p></cell>
						</row>			
					</tabular>
					<p/>
				</sidebyside>
			</statement>
		</lemma>

		<example xml:id="example-sqrt">
		<!--<title><em><term>Computations in a Matrix</term></em></title>-->
			<p/>
			<p>
				Let
				<me>
					A = \left[
					\begin{matrix}
						9 	\amp	0\\
						16 	\amp	4\\
						25 	\amp	1\\
					\end{matrix}\right].
				</me>
			</p>

			<p>
				Give the command that computes the square root of all the values in <c>A</c>.
			</p>

			<p/>

			<solution>
				<p>
					Running the commands
					<sidebyside width="100%">
						<program language="matlab">
							<code>
								A = [9 0;16 4;25 1];
								sqrt(A)
							</code>
						</program>
					</sidebyside>
				</p>

				<p>
					gives the output
					<sidebyside width="100%">
						<program language="matlab">
							<code>
								sqrt_A =

									3     0
									4     2
									5     1
							</code>
						</program>
					</sidebyside>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</example>

	</paragraphs>

	<paragraphs xml:id="row-column-wise-functions">
	<title><insert>Row/Column-Wise Functions</insert></title><p/>

		<p>
			MATLAB also contains a huge library of functions that perform common programming tasks on a list of numbers. For example, we may want the find the sum or maximum value of this list. It is natural to think of a list as a row or column vector and MATLAB can easily sum a list of such values. However, MATLAB goes a bit further by allowing you to sum several lists at once. Let's take a closer look at this idea.  
		</p>

		<p>
			A fundamental concept needed in many applications is to find the sum or product of a list of numbers.
		</p>
		
		<lemma xml:id="sum-prod-vector-syntax">
		<title><em><c>sum</c> and <c>prod</c> functions (vector)</em></title><p/>
			<statement>
				<sidebyside widths="81% 19%">
					<tabular>
						<col width="20%"/>
						<col width="80%"/>
						<row bottom="minor">
							<cell colspan="2"><p>Let <c>v</c> be a row vector (<m>m \times 1</m>) or column vector (<m>1 \times n</m>).</p></cell>
						</row>
						<row>
							<cell><p>Command</p></cell>
							<cell><c>result = sum(v)</c></cell>
						</row>
						<row valign="top" bottom="minor">
							<cell><p>Output</p></cell>
							<cell>
								<p>
									<c>result</c> is equal to the sum of all the elements in <c>v</c>.
								</p>
							</cell>
						</row>
						<row>
							<cell><p>Command</p></cell>
							<cell><c>result = prod(v)</c></cell>
						</row>
						<row valign="top">
							<cell><p>Output</p></cell>
							<cell>
								<p>
									<c>result</c> isequal to the product of all the elements in <c>v</c>.
								</p>
							</cell>
						</row>
					</tabular>
					<p/>
				</sidebyside>
			</statement>
		</lemma>
		
		<p>
			Another common task is to get the maximum or minimum from a list of values.
		</p>

		<lemma xml:id="min-max-vector-syntax">
		<title><em><c>min</c> and <c>max</c> functions (vector)</em></title><p/>
			<statement>
				<sidebyside widths="84% 16%">
					<tabular>
						<col width="20%"/>
						<col width="80%"/>
						<row bottom="minor">
							<cell colspan="2"><p>Let <c>v</c> be a row vector (<m>m \times 1</m>) or column vector (<m>1 \times n</m>).</p></cell>
						</row>
						<row>
							<cell><p>Command</p></cell>
							<cell><c>result = min(v)</c></cell>
						</row>
						<row valign="top" bottom="minor">
							<cell><p>Output</p></cell>
							<cell>
								<p>
									<c>result</c> is equal to the minimum of all the elements in <c>v</c>.
								</p>
							</cell>
						</row>
						<row>
							<cell><p>Command</p></cell>
							<cell><c>result = max(v)</c></cell>
						</row>
						<row valign="top">
							<cell><p>Output</p></cell>
							<cell>
								<p>
									<c>result</c> is equal to the maximum of all the elements in <c>v</c>.
								</p>
							</cell>
						</row>
					</tabular>
					<p/>
				</sidebyside>
			</statement>
		</lemma>

		<example xml:id="example-vector-sum-min-max"><p/>
			<p/>
			
			<p>
				Let
				<me>
					v = \left[
					\begin{matrix}
						10	\\
						6		\\
						-1	\\
					\end{matrix}\right].
				</me>
			</p>

			<p>
				Give the command that 
				<ol>
					<li>defines <c>sum_v</c> as the sum of the values in <c>v</c>.</li>
					<li>defines <c>prod_v</c> as the product of the values in <c>v</c>.</li>
					<li>defines <c>min_v</c> as the minimum of the values in <c>v</c>.</li>
					<li>defines <c>max_v</c> as the maximum of the values in <c>v</c>.</li>
				</ol>
			</p>

			<p/>

			<solution>
				<p>
					Running the commands
					<sidebyside width="100%">
						<program language="matlab">
							<code>
								v = [10; 6; -1];
								sum_v = sum(v)
								prod_v = prod(v)
								min_v = min(v)
								max_v = max(v)
							</code>
						</program>
					</sidebyside>
				</p>

				<p>
					produces the output
					<sidebyside width="100%">
						<program language="matlab">
							<code>
								sum_v = 15
								prod_v = -60
								min_v =	-1
								max_v = 10
							</code>
						</program>
					</sidebyside>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</example>

		<p>
			The above example shows how common functions apply to a vector, but what about a matrix? It turns out that MATLAB treats a matrix as a list of column vectors and applies the function to each column.  The output is a row vector containing the result of the function applied to each column. Visually, if
			<me>
				A = \left[
				\begin{matrix}
					9	\amp	1	\amp	7	\\
					5	\amp	2	\amp	1	\\
					9	\amp	3	\amp	0	\\
				\end{matrix}
				\right]
			</me>
			then the <c>sum(A)</c> and <c>max(A)</c> would be computed, column-wise, like so,
		</p>

		<tabular halign="center">
			<row>
				<cell>
					<image halign = "left" width="90%" xml:id="column-wise-sum-diagram">
						<latex-image>
							\begin{tikzpicture}
								\matrixbrackets{4}{-2.3}{0.7}
								\node [rect node 2] (1) at (-1.7, 2.5) {${\color{blue}
								\begin{array}{c}
										\!\!9\!\!\\\\
										\!\!5\!\!\\\\
										\!\!9\!\!
									\end{array}}$};

								\node [rect node 2] (3) at (-0.8, 2.5) {${\color{red}
									\begin{array}{c}
										\!\!1\!\!\\\\
										\!\!2\!\!\\\\
										\!\!3\!\!
									\end{array}}$};

								\node [rect node 2] (5) at (0.1, 2.5) {${\color{orange}
									\begin{array}{c}
										\!\!7\!\!\\\\
										\!\!1\!\!\\\\
										\!\!0\!\!
									\end{array}}$};
								
								\matrixbrackets[-0.7]{0.1}{-2.0}{0.9}
								\node [circle node 2] (2) at (-1.4, -0.3) {\color{blue}$24$};
								\node [circle node 2] (4) at (-0.5, -0.3) {\color{red}$6$};
								\node [circle node 2] (6) at (0.4, -0.3) {\color{orange}$8$};

								\node[label={[label distance=0.5cm,text depth=-1ex,rotate=-75]right:sum}] at (-1.8,1.6) {};
								\node[label={[label distance=0.5cm,text depth=-1ex,rotate=-75]right:sum}] at (-0.9,1.6) {};
								\node[label={[label distance=0.5cm,text depth=-1ex,rotate=-75]right:sum}] at (0.0,1.6) {};

								\draw [-&gt;, bend left=0, looseness=0] (1.south) to (2.north);
								\draw [-&gt;, bend left=0, looseness=0] (3.south) to (4.north);
								\draw [-&gt;, bend left=0, looseness=0] (5.south) to (6.north);
								
								\draw [-, bend left=30, looseness=0.4] (-2.5, 0.9) to (-2.5, 4.1);
								\draw [-, bend left=-30, looseness=0.4] (0.9, 0.9) to (0.9, 4.1);
								\node[label] (0) at (-3.2,2.5) {sum};
							\end{tikzpicture}
						</latex-image>
					</image>
				</cell>
				<cell>
					<image halign = "left" width="90%" xml:id="column-wise-max-diagram">
						<latex-image>
							\begin{tikzpicture}
								\matrixbrackets{4}{-2.3}{0.7}
								\node [rect node 2] (1) at (-1.7, 2.5) {
									\color{blue}{$
									\begin{array}{c}
										\!\!9\!\!\\\\
										\!\!5\!\!\\\\
										\!\!9\!\!
									\end{array}
									$}};

								\node [rect node 2] (3) at (-0.8, 2.5) {
									\color{red}{$
									\begin{array}{c}
										\!\!1\!\!\\\\
										\!\!2\!\!\\\\
										\!\!3\!\!
									\end{array}
									$}};

								\node [rect node 2] (5) at (0.1, 2.5) {
									\color{orange}{$
									\begin{array}{c}
										\!\!7\!\!\\\\
										\!\!1\!\!\\\\
										\!\!0\!\!
									\end{array}
									$}};
								
								\matrixbrackets[-0.7]{0.1}{-2.0}{0.9}
								\node [circle node 2] (2) at (-1.4, -0.3) {\color{blue}{$9$}};
								\node [circle node 2] (4) at (-0.5, -0.3) {\color{red}{$3$}};
								\node [circle node 2] (6) at (0.4, -0.3) {\color{orange}{$7$}};

								\node[label={[label distance=0.5cm,text depth=-1ex,rotate=-75]right:max}] at (-1.8,1.6) {};
								\node[label={[label distance=0.5cm,text depth=-1ex,rotate=-75]right:max}] at (-0.9,1.6) {};
								\node[label={[label distance=0.5cm,text depth=-1ex,rotate=-75]right:max}] at (0.0,1.6) {};

								\draw [-&gt;, bend left=0, looseness=0] (1.south) to (2.north);
								\draw [-&gt;, bend left=0, looseness=0] (3.south) to (4.north);
								\draw [-&gt;, bend left=0, looseness=0] (5.south) to (6.north);
								
								\draw [-, bend left=30, looseness=0.4] (-2.5, 0.9) to (-2.5, 4.1);
								\draw [-, bend left=-30, looseness=0.4] (0.9, 0.9) to (0.9, 4.1);
								\node[label] (0) at (-3.2,2.5) {max};
							\end{tikzpicture}
						</latex-image>
					</image>
				</cell>
			</row>
		</tabular>

		<p>
			This is the default behavior, but you can easily tell MATLAB to apply the function to the rows instead of the columns.
		</p>

		<lemma xml:id="sum-prod-matrix-syntax">
		<title><em><c>sum</c> and <c>prod</c> functions (matrix)</em></title><p/>
			<statement>
				<tabular>
					<col width="15%"/>
					<col width="85%"/>
					<row bottom="minor">
						<cell colspan="2"><p>Let <c>A</c> be a matrix (<m>m \times n</m>).</p></cell>
					</row>
					<row>
						<cell><p>Command</p></cell>
						<cell><c>result = sum(A)</c> or <c>result = sum(A,1)</c></cell>
					</row>
					<row valign="top" bottom="minor">
						<cell><p>Output</p></cell>
						<cell>
							<p>
								<c>result</c> is a <m>1 \times n</m> matrix (row vector) that contains the sum of the elements in each column of <c>A</c>.
							</p>
						</cell>
					</row>
					<row>
						<cell><p>Command</p></cell>
						<cell><c>result = sum(A,2)</c></cell>
					</row>
					<row valign="top" bottom="minor">
						<cell><p>Output</p></cell>
						<cell>
							<p>
								<c>result</c> is a <m>m \times 1</m> matrix (column vector) that contains the sum of the elements in each row of <c>A</c>.
							</p>
						</cell>
					</row>
					<row>
						<cell><p>Command</p></cell>
						<cell><c>result = sum(sum(A))</c></cell>
					</row>
					<row valign="top" bottom="minor">
						<cell><p>Output</p></cell>
						<cell>
							<p>
								<c>result</c> is a <m>1 \times 1</m> matrix (number) that contains the sum of all elements in <c>A</c>.
							</p>
						</cell>
					</row>
					<row>
						<cell><p>Command</p></cell>
						<cell><c>result = prod(v)</c> or <c>result = prod(A,1)</c></cell>
					</row>
					<row valign="top" bottom="minor">
						<cell><p>Output</p></cell>
						<cell>
							<p>
								<c>result</c> is a <m>1 \times n</m> matrix (row vector) that contains the product of the elements in each column of <c>A</c>.
							</p>
						</cell>
					</row>
					<row>
						<cell><p>Command</p></cell>
						<cell><c>result = prod(A,2)</c></cell>
					</row>
					<row valign="top" bottom="minor">
						<cell><p>Output</p></cell>
						<cell>
							<p>
								<c>result</c> is a <m>m \times 1</m> matrix (column vector) that contains the product of the elements in each row of <c>A</c>.
							</p>
						</cell>
					</row>
					<row>
						<cell><p>Command</p></cell>
						<cell><c>result = prod(prod(A))</c></cell>
					</row>
					<row valign="top">
						<cell><p>Output</p></cell>
						<cell>
							<p>
								<c>result</c> is a <m>1 \times 1</m> matrix (number) that contains the product of all elements in <c>A</c>.
							</p>
						</cell>
					</row>
				</tabular>
			</statement>
		</lemma>

		<example xml:id="example-matrix-sum"><p/>
			<p/>
			
			<p>
				Let
				<me>
					A = \left[
					\begin{matrix}
						1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp 4	\\
						5 \amp 6 \amp 7 \amp 8	
					\end{matrix}\right].
				</me>
			</p>

			<p>
				Give the command that 
				<ol marker="a">
					<li>defines <c>c_sum</c> as the sum of the values in each column of <c>A</c>.</li>
					<li>defines <c>r_sum</c> as the sum of the values in each row of <c>A</c>.</li>
					<li>defines <c>t_sum</c> as the sum of all the values in <c>A</c>.</li>
				</ol>
			</p>

			<p/>

			<solution>
				<p>
					Define <c>A</c> first, of course
					<sidebyside width="100%">
						<program language="matlab">
							<code>
								>> A = [1 2 3 4;5 6 7 8];
							</code>
						</program>
					</sidebyside>
				</p>

				<p>
					For the column sums, use
					<sidebyside widths="50% 50%">
						<p>
							Command:
							<program language="matlab">
								<code>
									>> c_sum = sum(A)  % or
									>> c_sum = sum(A,1)
								</code>
							</program>
						</p>
						<p>
							Output:
							<program language="matlab">
								<code>
									c_sum =
										6     8    10    12
								</code>
							</program>
						</p>
					</sidebyside>
					For the row sums, use
					<sidebyside widths="50% 50%">
						<p>
							Command:
							<program language="matlab">
								<code>
									>> r_sum = sum(A,2)
								</code>
							</program>
						</p>
						<p>
							Output:
							<program language="matlab">
								<code>
									r_sum =
										10
										26
								</code>
							</program>
						</p>
					</sidebyside>
					Finally, we have a few options for the sum of all the elements. We can use the
					<sidebyside widths="50% 50%">
						<p>
							Command:
							<program language="matlab">
								<code>
									>> t_sum = sum(c_sum)  % or
									>> t_sum = sum(r_sum)  % or
									>> t_sum = sum(sum(A))
								</code>
							</program>
						</p>
						<p>
							Output:
							<program language="matlab">
								<code>
									t_sum =
										36
								</code>
							</program>
						</p>
					</sidebyside>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</example>

		<lemma xml:id="min-max-matrix-syntax">
		<title><em><c>min</c> and <c>max</c> functions (matrix)</em></title><p/>
			<statement>
				<sidebyside widths="100% 0%">
					<tabular>
						<col width="10%"/>
						<col width="90%"/>
						<row bottom="minor">
							<cell colspan="2"><p>Let <c>A</c> be a matrix (<m>m \times n</m>).</p></cell>
						</row>
						<row>
							<cell><p>Command</p></cell>
							<cell><c>result = min(A)</c> or <c>result = min(A,1)</c></cell>
						</row>
						<row valign="top" bottom="minor">
							<cell><p>Output</p></cell>
							<cell>
								<p>
									<c>result</c> is a <m>1 \times n</m> matrix (row vector) that contains the minimum element in each column of <c>A</c>
								</p>
							</cell>
						</row>
						<row>
							<cell><p>Command</p></cell>
							<cell><c>result = min(A,2)</c></cell>
						</row>
						<row valign="top" bottom="minor">
							<cell><p>Output</p></cell>
							<cell>
								<p>
									<c>result</c> is a <m>m \times 1</m> matrix (column vector) that contains the minimum element in each row of <c>A</c>
								</p>
							</cell>
						</row>
						<row>
							<cell><p>Command</p></cell>
							<cell><c>result = min(min(A))</c></cell>
						</row>
						<row valign="top" bottom="minor">
							<cell><p>Output</p></cell>
							<cell>
								<p>
									<c>result</c> is a <m>1 \times 1</m> matrix (number) that contains the minimum of all elements in <c>A</c>
								</p>
							</cell>
						</row>
						<row>
							<cell><p>Command</p></cell>
							<cell><c>result = max(v)</c> or <c>result = max(A,1)</c></cell>
						</row>
						<row valign="top" bottom="minor">
							<cell><p>Output</p></cell>
							<cell>
								<p>
									<c>result</c> is a <m>1 \times n</m> matrix (row vector) that contains the maximum element in each column of <c>A</c>
								</p>
							</cell>
						</row>
						<row>
							<cell><p>Command</p></cell>
							<cell><c>result = max(A,2)</c></cell>
						</row>
						<row valign="top" bottom="minor">
							<cell><p>Output</p></cell>
							<cell>
								<p>
									<c>result</c> is a <m>m \times 1</m> matrix (column vector) that contains the maximum element in each row of <c>A</c>
								</p>
							</cell>
						</row>
						<row>
							<cell><p>Command</p></cell>
							<cell><c>result = max(max(A))</c></cell>
						</row>
						<row valign="top">
							<cell><p>Output</p></cell>
							<cell>
								<p>
									<c>result</c> is a <m>1 \times 1</m> matrix (number) that contains the maximum of all elements in <c>A</c>
								</p>
							</cell>
						</row>
					</tabular>
					<p/>
				</sidebyside>
			</statement>
		</lemma>

		<example xml:id="example-matrix-min-max"><p/>
			<p/>
			
			<p>
				Let
				<me>
					A = \left[
					\begin{matrix}
						1 \amp 0 \amp 3\\
						8 \amp -1 \amp 3\\
						1 \amp 7 \amp 3	\\
						5 \amp 16 \amp 8	
					\end{matrix}\right].
				</me>
			</p>

			<p>
				Give the command that 
				<ol marker="a">
					<li>defines <c>c_min</c> as the minimum of the values in each column of <c>A</c>.</li>
					<li>defines <c>r_min</c> as the minimum of the values in each row of <c>A</c>.</li>
					<li>defines <c>t_min</c> as the minimum of all the values in <c>A</c>.</li>
				</ol>
			</p>

			<p/>

			<solution>
				<p>
					Define <c>A</c> first, of course
					<sidebyside width="100%">
						<program language="matlab">
							<code>
								>> A = [1 0 3; 8 -1 3; 1 7 3; 5 16 8];
							</code>
						</program>
					</sidebyside>
				</p>

				<p>
					For the column mins, use
					<sidebyside widths="50% 50%">
						<p>
							Command:
							<program language="matlab">
								<code>
									>> c_min = min(A)  % or
									>> c_min = min(A,[],1)
								</code>
							</program>
						</p>
						<p>
							Output:
							<program language="matlab">
								<code>
									c_min =
							    	1    -1     3
								</code>
							</program>
						</p>
					</sidebyside>
					For the row mins, use
					<sidebyside widths="50% 50%">
						<p>
							Command:
							<program language="matlab">
								<code>
									>> r_min = min(A,[],2)
								</code>
							</program>
						</p>
						<p>
							Output:
							<program language="matlab">
								<code>
									r_min =

										0
										-1
										1
										5
								</code>
							</program>
						</p>
					</sidebyside>
					Finally, we have a few options for the min of all the elements. We can use the
					<sidebyside widths="50% 50%">
						<p>
							Command:
							<program language="matlab">
								<code>
									>> t_min = min(c_min)  % or
									>> t_min = min(r_min)  % or
									>> t_min = min(min(A))
								</code>
							</program>
						</p>
						<p>
							Output:
							<program language="matlab">
								<code>
									t_min =
										-1
								</code>
							</program>
						</p>
					</sidebyside>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</example>

	</paragraphs>
</section> 